application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved
description: Phased redevelopment and part refurbishment of site/buildings (currently used for general industrial/storage, offices and sports complex purposes) which straddle both London Boroughs, to provide mixed use, 1-8 storeys,  development on 'urban village' principles, comprising 705 residential units including 18 live/work units (446 one, two and three bedroom flats and 259 three, four and five bedroom houses - 3088 habitable rooms overall), and non residential/commercial as follows - 7900 sq metres new offices, 7520 sq metres refurbished offices, 680 sq metres light industrial/workshops retained for use as managed workspace, 100 sq metres wardens office/meeting rooms, 100 sq metres tele-working centre, 560 sq metres retail, 550 sq metres community facilities, 240 sq metres restaurant, 480 sq metres creche, 200 sq metres ancillary commercial floorspace to canal basin area, 1500 sq metres separate health facility, 4945 sq metres sports complex, together with childrens' play/adventure play areas, youth shelter, sports pitches, parkland landscaping and wildlife area, new canal basin, new bridge over canal and rebuilding of existing bridge, amenity open space, road infrastructure - with vehicular access from Ruislip Road and Broadmead Road, and associated servicing and car parking (Outline application with Environmental Impact Assessment)
decision_conditions: Prior  to the commencement of development on each relevant phase, details of the siting, design, external appearance and landscaping ( called the "reserved matters" ) shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority in writing for the relevant phase of the development.  For the purposes of this condition, development shall not include a). demolition, remediation of contamination, and associated earth works in respect of details of siting, design and external appearance, and b). demolition in respect of landscaping.    REASON:  The application, which is in outline form only and, therefore, not accompanied by full detailed plans, is for a phased development for which it is considered that demolition, remediation and associated earth works, need not await full detailed approval of all the reserved matters. | Application for the approval of all the reserved matters shall be made to the Local Planning Authority before the expiration of seven years from the date of this permission.   REASON:  In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990, and in consideration of the proposed intention to phase the development. | The development permitted shall be begun either before the expiration of five years from the date of this permission or before the expiration of two years from the date of approval of the last of the reserved matters to be approved, whichever is the later.   REASON:  In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.   3A.  Prior to the commencement of any development on the site, details of site preparation works -  including remedial works and the method of dealing with contaminated ground on the site (also including details of, and a method of disposal of, material to be removed from the site, if any, and the recycling of material arising from the demolition works to be re-used within the development ) - shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority.  The approved works shall be carried out as approved in conjunction with the implementation of the development. No materials shall be removed from the site other than with the approval of the Local Planning Authority. This condition shall be read in conjunction with conditions Nos. 8 and 9 of this consent.     REASON:  In order to ensure that details of site remediation, and of recycling and material disposal, are approved before the development commences, and in the interest of sustainability, maintaining existing trees and hedgerows wherever possible, and minimising the impact on local roads during demolition and construction.      3B.  Prior to the commencement of development, other than demolition, remediation of contamination and site preparation works, details of phasing of the development, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The proposals shall be carried out in accordance with the approved phasing. Where, elsewhere in these conditions, reference is made to a relevant phase of the development that shall mean a phase as described in the approved phasing programme.   REASON:  To ensure that any phasing of the development is properly co-ordinated and carried out in the sequence agreed by the local planning authority, in the interest of neighbouring amenity and the safety and free flow of vehicular and pedestrian traffic on the neighbouring highways.    3C.  In conjunction with the details to be submitted pursuant to condition 1 in respect of the first phase of development, a landscape and open space master strategy for the entire application site shall be submitted  for approval to the Local Planning Authority.  No development other than demolition shall be commenced until the approval of the Local Planning Authority has been obtained in writing to the strategy.  The provisions of the approved strategy shall be incorporated in the subsequent applications for the approval of the matters reserved by condition 1.   This strategy shall include proposals for : i) the overall landscape framework and landscape design concept ii) landscape features to be retained as part of development iii) typical landscaping treatment for housing areas and the neighbourhood/village centre iv) details of any ground modelling and associated landscaping treatment v) the location and a specification for the provision of public open space, play spaces and amenity areas vi) the timing of structural landscpe works and planting    REASON:  In order to ensure that the phases of the development follow an approved overall strategy for landscaping. | The development permitted, as indicated on the indicative Master Plan Drawing No. 101Rev. E, shall not exceed a density within the London Borough of Ealing, which taken with the proposed part of the development in the London Borough of Hillingdon, gives rise to an overall density of 300.1 habitable rooms per hectare ( not accounting for the non residential uses in the residential areas ), unless otherwise approved by the Local Planning Authority. This condition should be seen in conjunction with Condition No. 24 of this consent    REASON:  To ensure that the site is not overdeveloped, in the interests of maintaining the visual character of the area, and ensuring satisfactory living conditions for future occupiers of the site and existing neighbouring occupiers. | Samples of the materials to be used for the external surfaces of the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for the relevant phase of development before any part of the relevant phase is commenced. Development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.    REASON:  To ensure that the materials harmonise with the surroundings. | Development, excluding demolition works, shall not begin, or shall not begin on a particular phase of the development, until details of site drainage works have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for the relevant phase of the development. The scheme for site drainage as approved shall be carried out in conjunction with the relevant phase of the development.   REASON:  To ensure that adequate drainage of the site is carried out as approved, and that there is no pollution of the water environment. | Details of dustbin and enclosed refuse storage areas, which shall include recycling ( as well as composting ) and waste facilities the relevant phase of the development, shall be submitted to and shall be approved in writing by the local planning authority, prior to the commencement of construction of buildings on that particular phase of development, and these details shall show such facilities to be sited no greater than 23 metres ( 10 metres where paladins are employed ) from the highway, and a maximum of 25 metres from any dwelling unit intended to use them.  Such provision as may be approved following the submission of details shall be provided and brought into use prior to the first occupation of the relevant part of the development and shall thereafter be retained permanently.     REASON:  To comply with the Council's Design Standards, to ensure that the development can be adequately serviced in this respect, in the interests of sustainability, and to protect the living conditions of occupiers of the area. | Full details of both hard and soft landscaping works for each relevant phase of the development including a phased programme of works, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, prior to commencement of the relevant phase of the development.  The works as approved shall be undertaken in accordance with the programme agreed by the Local Planning Authority. Any trees or other plants which die or are removed within the first five years following the implementation of the landscaping scheme shall be replaced during the next planting season. The planting scheme shall include planting within the ten metres wide buffer zone adjoining the canal to be provided in accordance with a condition of this consent. There shall also be planting of suitable marginal and aquatic species where the mooring function of the basin will not be impeded.    REASON:  To ensure that the development is landscaped in the interests of the visual character and appearance of the area, to ensure that the natural features of importance within or adjoining the watercourse are protected, restored or replaced, and to enhance the ecological value of the canal mooring basin. | No existing trees, hedgerows and shrubs within the site shall be lopped, felled, pruned or otherwise affected in any way ( including raising or lowering the soil levels under the crown spread of the trees, the hedges or the shrubs), and no excavation shall be cut under the crown spread of the tress, the hedges or the shrubs, until the submission to and approval in writing by the Local Planning Authority of a scheme for their removal, pruning or otherwise; such scheme as is approved shall be implemented and those existing trees, hedgerows and shrubs identified on the plan subsequently approved for retention shall not be destroyed nor shall they be uprooted, felled or pruned for a period of five years after completion of the permitted development or the particular phase of the permitted development.  Any trees, shrubs, or hedgerows which die or are  damaged or diseased before the end of that period shall be replaced with new trees, shrubs or hedgerows of a size, species, and in such numbers, as may be agreed in writing, by the local planning authority before the  end of the first planting season following their loss or removal.   REASON:  In the interests of the visual character and appearance of the area and in reflection of the site's nature conservation value. | The entire root system of trees to be retained, following approval of a scheme for such retention pursuant to a condition of this consent, indicated by the spread of their branches, shall be protected by stout exclusion fencing until completion of the development or that phase of the development, and the area beneath the spread of the branches of the trees to be retained shall not be used for the storage of building materials, plant, machinery, or other items, or for vehicular access or for the burning of materials of any kind.   REASON:  To prevent damage to the trees in the interest of the visual character and appearance of the area and the site's nature conservation value. | Any tree works which may be authorised shall be carried out to the latest requirements of British Standard 3998 "Recommendations for Tree Work".   REASON:  To safeguard the trees in the interest of the visual character of the area and the site's nature conservation value. | Details of a full ecological survey, to include all statutorily protected species, and a management plan which shall include the outlining of a working methodology for dealing with any potential protected fauna or flora during construction and demolition works and after the development hereby permitted has been completed, shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority in respect of each phase of the development, prior to commencement of any construction on the relevant phase of the development, and, in respect of the ecological survey, demolition works.  The management plan shall also outline proposals for the retention of current features of interest within the site and for the mitigation of any adverse impact on local ecology arising from the development. This shall be in addition to proposals for "substantial " ecological enhancement, and provision of a system of management post development.  The provisions of the approved ecology management plan shall be implemented in phases in conjunction with the approved details.    REASON:  In the interests of the site's nature conservation value and potential. | Unless the Local Planning Authority decides otherwise, no construction of buildings shall take place in respect of a particular phase of the development, until there has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, a plan indicating the positions, design, materials and type of boundary treatment to be erected, in respect of that phase of the development. The boundary treatment shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details and shall be carried out prior to the completion of the relevant phase of the development for which the details have been submitted.    REASON:  To protect the visual appearance of the area, the living conditions of potential occupiers of the development and neighbouring occupiers, and to ensure that sightlines for vehicular traffic on adjoining highways is not prejudiced. | Details of the network of proposed internal access roads, including the roads which are to serve as bus routes, shall be provided to the standards required by the local planning authority.  Such details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of construction on that particular phase of the development, and the road network as approved shall be provided and constructed in accordance with the specifications contained within the Design Guide for Road and Sewer Works on New Development (March 1992 ), in conjunction with Grand Union Village - Southall (291) Highway Design Guidelines - February 2002, and all other relevant standards, and brought into use before the relevant phase of the development is occupied, and shall thereafter be retained.    REASON:  In the interest of the safety and free flow of both vehicular and pedestrian traffic. | Details of cycle storage/ parking provision, in accordance with the standards adopted by the Local Planning Authority, for the relevant phase of the development, shall be submitted to, and shall be approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of the construction of buildings in respect of the relevant phase.  Such details shall indicate secure and covered provision, and ancillary shower facilities in any building to be used for office/ industrial or sports/ leisure purposes, and any details which are approved shall be implemented and made available for use at the first occupation of the relevant part of the relevant phase of the development and shall thereafter be retained.     REASON:  To ensure that adequate provision for cyclists is made within the development. | Notwithstanding condition No. 3B of this consent, before any construction in any phase of the development is commenced,  details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority of any temporary measures relating to the redirection of traffic for the duration of the construction works on that respective phase of development. The details as approved shall be implemented as approved.  REASON:  To ensure that neighbouring amenity and the safety and free flow of vehicular and pedestrian traffic on the neighbouring highways is not prejudiced. | Construction of buildings and roads in the relevant phase of the development, shall not be commenced until details of the junctions between the proposed roads and parking areas forming part of the development and the existing highways have been approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, and the development or the relevant phase of the development, shall not be occupied until the junctions have been constructed in accordance with the approved details.  Such details shall include the two proposed new points of vehicular access to Broadmead Road within the London Borough of Ealing, and the new and the altered ( i.e. Taywood Road ) vehicular access points to Ruislip Road, and the vehicular and emergency access points to Adrienne Avenue, the positions of which are indicated on the submitted Master Plan Drawing No. 101 Rev.E.  REASON:  In the interest of the maintenance of adequate sight lines and the safety and free flow of both vehicular and pedestrian traffic on the adjoining highways. | Details of off-street car parking provision, to include provision of parking for disabled persons, to serve the relevant phase of development, shall be submitted to, and shall be approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority, and such provision as is approved shall be provided prior to occupation of that phase of the development, and shall thereafter be retained. The details shall be in accordance with the standards adopted by the Local Planning Authority, except that the provision for social housing shall average 0.6 of one space for each unit, and the three refurbished office buildings ( refurbished zones 2, 6 and 7 - the Glaxo building ), as shown in illustrative form on the indicative Master Plan, shall be to the statutorily Adopted standard of a maximum of one parking space per 47 sq metres of floorspace, but that the parking provision for the new office building shall be to the standard of a maximum of one space per 100 sq metres of floor space.     REASON:  To ensure the provision of appropriate levels of parking, disabled access, and in the interest of the safety and free flow of traffic on the adjoining highways, and of sustainable development through the encouragement of the use of other forms of transport. | Details of service vehicle parking spaces, access, and loading, unloading and manoeuvring areas, in accordance with the standards of the Local Planning Authority, shall be submitted to, and shall be approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority, prior to the commencement of the construction of the relevant phase of the development, and such details as are approved shall be implemented before occupation of the relevant phase of the development and shall thereafter be retained.  REASON:  To ensure that adequate servicing space is available within the site. | Details of the network of internal pedestrian and cycle routes for the relevant phase of the development, in accordance with the principles illustrated on the Master Plan drawing No. 101E, shall be submitted to and shall be approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of the construction of the relevant phase of the development, and the details as are approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of the relevant phase of the development and shall thereafter be retained.   REASON:  To promote sustainable forms of transport and in the interest of highway safety. | The scheme of remedial works submitted pursuant to condition No. 3A shall include details of appropriate measures to prevent pollution of groundwater and surface water, including provisions for monitoring.  The measures as approved shall then be implemented, and the development shall only proceed in strict accordance with these measures.  REASON:  Remedial measures must prevent pollution of the water environment. | A 10 metres wide, or as may otherwise be agreed by the Local Planning Authority,  landscape buffer zone, alongside the Grand Union Canal shall be established in accordance with details which shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before building works are commenced on any adjoining part of the development.  This buffer zone shall be free from roads ( excluding footways and cycleways ), car parking, fences and new buildings and where possible gardens, and should be suitably landscaped with local native species.  The buffer zone shall be provided in accordance with the details as approved before the first occupation of any adjoining part of the development, and shall thereafter be retained.  REASON:   To maintain the character of the canal as a Conservation Area and a wildlife corridor and provide undisturbed refuges for wildlife using the waterway corridor. | A scheme for protecting sensitive rooms/ balconies/gardens from external noise, to the following criteria, shall be submitted to and shall be approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of the development or the relevant phase of the development, and such details as may be approved shall be implemented, prior to the first occupation of those rooms/ balconies/ gardens in the development or the relevant phase of the development..  The scheme which shall be submitted shall be to the following criteria:  Noise levels at the following locations shall not exceed -  Private gardens and balconies - not greater than 50dB(A)Leq, 1 hour (07:00 - 23:00 hrs.) Bedrooms - not greater than 30 dB(A)Leq, 1 hour (23:00 - 07:00 hrs.) Living rooms and dining rooms - not greater than 35 dB(A)Leq, 1 hour (07:00 - 23:00 hrs.), and Kitchens, bathrooms and utility rooms - not greater than 45 dB(A)Leq, 1 hour (07:00 - 23:00 hrs.).  REASON:  In the interest of  residential amenity. | The development shall be carried out in general accordance with the illustrative Master Plan ( Drawing No. 101E ), and associated application information, including that submitted as part of the accompanying Environmental Statement.  REASON:  To ensure that the approved scheme to be implemented is that assessed in the Environmental Statement. | Prior to the commencement of construction of any relevant building, details shall be submitted to, and approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority for any community buildings or sports halls or venues for events involving amplified music or speech, to demonstrate that the composite sound reduction index of the building envelope, Rw, is not less than 40 dB averaged over the frequency range 100 to 3150Hz, with windows shut and other means of ventilation provided.  Any details that may be approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of the building (s), and shall thereafter be retained.  For such venues, a suitable mechanical ventilation system shall be installed to ensure that doors and windows are kept closed during hot weather and the plant associated with this system shall be silenced to a standard not exceeding NR35 Leq, (5mins.) (23:00 - 07:00 hrs.), measured or calculated at 1 metre from the nearest facade of the nearest affected noise sensitive premises.   REASON:  In the interest of residential amenity. | Plant or equipment/ building services plant or installations associated with premises for commercial and community use, which is audible inside dwellings within the same building, shall be designed to satisfy an acoustic standard not exceeding NR 25 (Leq, 5 mins), 23:00 - 07:00 hrs. (bedrooms) and NR 30 (Leq, 1 hour), 07:00 - 23:00 hrs. (living rooms).  REASON:  In the interest of residential amenity. | Any machinery audible outside any buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided in accordance with this consent, shall be designed to an acoustic standard not exceeding Noise Rating NR 35 measured or calculated at the nearest horizontal or vertical boundary of the nearest affected dwelling, whichever is the closer.  REASON:  To protect the living conditions of neighbouring occupiers. | Details of all external lighting to be erected/ installed, in a relevant phase of the development, which shall pay due regard to low energy and other sustainable forms of lighting, demonstrating compliance with the recommendations of the Institution of Lighting Engineers "Guidance Notes for the Reduction of Light Pollution" and the provisions of BS 5489 Part 9, must be submitted in writing to, and approved by, the Local Planning authority, prior to the commencement of construction of the relevant phase of the development.  The lighting as approved must be installed prior to the first bringing into use of the development or relevant phase of the development, and shall thereafter be maintained in accordance with these standards.  The submitted details shall include vertical illumination levels and provisions for reducing glare.  REASON:  To ensure adequate levels of lighting, to ensure that sustainable lighting is considered for use where appropriate, to protect the living conditions of occupiers of the area, and to prevent light spillage prejudicing local amenity including within the vicinity of the canal. | Details of the hours of use and level of illumination of any floodlighting within the site shall be submitted to, and shall be approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority prior to the bringing into use of any such lighting, and the floodlighting shall only be provided for the hours of use and level of illumination as may be approved.  REASON:  In  the interest of residential amenity and local ecology. | Notwithstanding the provisions of Classes A, B, C, D, E and F, of Part 1 of Schedule 2 to the Town and Country Planning ( General Permitted Development ) Order 1995, no additions or extensions to any dwellinghouses which may subsequently be approved, including to their roofs, or alterations to the shape of any of the roofs of the dwellinghouses, or the erection or construction of any porch outside any external door of the dwellinghouses, or the provision within the curtilage of the dwellinghouses of any buildings or enclosure, or of any hardstandings to the front of any of the dwellinghouses, shall be carried out without the prior permission of the Local Planning Authority, obtained through the submission of a planning application.  REASON:  In order to prevent overdevelopment and increased density of this already high density development which would be harmful to the living conditions of occupiers of the area, and to ensure that the detailed design of the townscape is not harmed by incongruous development. | The roof space of any buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided shall not be converted into additional residential accommodation without the prior permission of the Local Planning Authority.  REASON:  In order to prevent overdevelopment and increased density of this already high density development which would be harmful to the living conditions of occupiers of the area. | Any domestic garages, including in any of the buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided for the storage of motor vehicles,  with the exception of  any live work units which may subsequently be approved in detail, shall only be used for domestic purposes and not for any industrial, commercial or business use, and no domestic garage in association with any residential accommodation shall be used to provide living accommodation which is separate and not incidental to that accommodation.  REASON:  In the interest of neighbouring amenity, and the safety and free flow of vehicular and pedestrian traffic. | Any flat roofs of any buildings or parts of buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided shall not be used to form a balcony, roof garden or similar amenity area, without the prior permission in writing of the Local Planning Authority obtained through the submission of a planning application.  REASON:  In order to protect the privacy, and other amenity, of neighbouring occupiers. | Details of the hours of use of any floorspace within buildings or associated land which is approved as part of this consent for purposes of  community facilities, health, creche, shop(s) and restaurant, and sports and leisure activities, and in particular any use requiring amplified music or speech, shall be submitted to, and approved in writing by, the Local Planning Authority, prior to the first bringing into use of such facilities, and the hours of use shall be implemented as approved and, shall, thereafter, be maintained.    REASON:  In the interest of the amenity of neighbouring occupiers. | Details of the hours of business/ use of any commercial floorspace within any buildings which may subsequently be approved and provided containing residential units, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the bringing into use of the business/use, and such hours of use as may be approved shall be implemented, and thereafter maintained.  REASON:  In the interest of the amenity of neighbouring and other occupiers. | Details for the relevant phase of the development of the layout of children's play areas for children of residents and visitors shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to construction of the particular phase of the development, being commenced, and such play areas as may be approved shall be provided in conjunction with the development or that relevant phase of the development.  REASON:  To ensure satisfactory development and provision of play facilities. | Ventilation ducts from commercial and community premises in the same building as dwellings shall be fixed to the building structure with suitable anti-vibration isolators, and fan motors shall be vibration isolated from ducts, so as to satisfy an acoustic standard of not exceeding NR25 (Leq, 5 mins.) inside a habitable room.    REASON:  In the interest of neighbouring residential amenity. | The details of all residential units to be provided pursuant to condition No.1, shall show as far as practicable, compliance with the standards for Lifetime Homes, or, in respect of the affordable housing units, shall provide accommodation to an equivalent standard under the Scheme Development Standards set by the Housing Development Corporation. All units shall meet the relevant requirements of Ealing's "Accessible Ealing" as updated. A proportion of the units, the details of which ( including numbers and locations ) shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority prior to the construction of the relevant phase of the development being commenced, shall be provided to the specifications for Wheelchair Housing as referred to in that document.  REASON:  To ensure adequate accessibility to the residential accommodation to be provided, by disabled persons, including those temporarily disabled and the ambulant disabled.
